Rating: 4
This pie was fabulous with the following changes: I used a frozen organic pie crust, which I let thaw and then pre-baked for 10 minutes. I used the crumb topping (cut the sugar in half and mix by hand - no processor) from the Deep-Dish Rhubarb Pie with Crumb Topping on this site instead of a double crust. I also used tapioca in place of cornstarch (same measurement), let the filling sit for 1 hour, and I didn't have nearly the excess liquid others mentioned. The crumb topping also helped soak some of it up. I recommend baking this pie on a cookie sheet lined with foil to contain the inevitable sticky spills. My baking times were 400 for 20 minutes, 350 for 20 minutes, then add the topping and bake for another 25 minutes. Keep the fruit in pretty large pieces. My partner said this was the "best pie ever!"

Rating: 2
Well, full disclosure: I'm a lazy so-and-so. I used store-bought crust, which has worked well for pies that I've made in the past BUT with this recipe, I really think it needs a flakier, more buttery crust. Pillsbury's is a bit doughy for this pie. If I should make this again, I'll make my crust, using the recipe here. As far as the filling is concerned, after reading the reviews, I let the fruit mixture sit for an hour, drained the juice, and simmered it in a saucepan until it thickened up a bit. I think this really helped, because I didn't experience any of the issues with bubbling over or runny filling that others had trouble with. I also cut the sugar, by about an eighth of a cup, because I don't like overly sweet things. This was a bad idea. The pie needs every bit of sugar that the recipe calls for, and maybe even a bit more than that...or perhaps I had exceptionally TART rhubarb (if there is such a thing). Also, (and I wish I'd read the reviews that talked about this beforehand), 1 teaspoon of cinnamon is TOO MUCH cinnamon. It overpowers the delicate flavors of strawberry and rhubarb. I would use 1/2 teaspoon if I make this again. I have a gas stove/oven, and I baked this pie at 400 degrees for 20 minutes, then covered the crust edges with aluminum and reduced the heat to 350 for 45 minutes. It came out perfectly done, so definitely take the recipe's cooking times with a grain of salt, and keep an eye on your pie.

