Rating: 3
COOKING TIME: I used disposable foil pans and the pie came out purfectly in the baking time specified by the recipe. I had no burning whatsoever and did not have to cover theedges with foil. I think some of the reviewers who have complained about burning might be using dark non-stick pans, and/or their ovens may run hot. --- THINGS I MIGHT DO DIFFERENTLY: 1) It could use a little more zing, so I might increase rhubarb ratio, 2) experiment with reducing the amount of cornstarch, 3) experiment with the addition of a bit of vanilla --- THE PIE CRUST: To the cook from West virginia who commented on the softness of the dough after coming out of the food processor... I made this crust twice because I had the same thing happen on the first try. It's basically the result of overmixing the dough in the food processor and the friction generating enough heat to melt the butter and shortening. When this happens, the cooked crust seems to come out more like a tender shortbread rather than a flaky pie crust. I disregarded the mixing directions on the second try... I made a second batch by hand instead of in the food processor, making sure my shortening and butter were VERY VERY cold, and the resulting consistency was totally different. It was difficult to roll out without tearing, but the result was a much flakier crust. Patching the tears with loose pieces worked fine. Enjoy!

