Is there anything that says spring better than strawberries, rhubarb, and pie? I think not-- and this was a wonderful way to showcase the season's bounty. The crust is possibly the most flaky I've ever eaten, lovely and delicate. I used lard in place of the shortening, which may have done the trick. I didn't even bother to lattice the dough, though I'm sure it would have been gorgeous. Be careful adding the water-- I used only six tablespoons, and it was almost too much. One of best things about this recipe is that the dough turns out to be more than enough, so there's no need to skimp. I covered my pie with foil at point where you're supposed to lower the temperature of the oven. While the pie baked, however, part of the edge kind of drooped off, and fell into the oven. Any ideas why? Oh well, it still looked wonderful, and the filling was likewise divine (I used tapioca instead of the cornstarch, which I find masks the flavor of the fruit too much). I'm sure to make this one again (perhaps with a teaspoon or so of vanilla, as suggested).

